TY  - JOUR
T1  - Compensation in Organizations: Current Research and Practice
AU  - Mahoney, Joseph T.
AU  - Kulik, Carol T.
Y1  - 2001/01/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.4011992
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2001.4011992
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 128
EP  - 130
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - How can researchers bridge the gap between compensation theory and the compensation pressures today's complex organizations face? The book ?Compensation in Organizations: Current Research and Practice,? edited by Sara L. Rynes and Barry Gerhart, tackles this problem head-on. This book is squarely aimed at academic researchers, and Rynes and Gerhart know their audience. Each chapter begins with a brief ?state-of-the-field? overview, addressing a defined segment of compensation research and theory. The chapter authors then identify compensation issues and practices that current knowledge does not address. In essence, in each chapter a research agenda for the applied researcher is laid out. The book does a great job of identifying the ?holes? that have not been addressed by the compensation literature; there are enough research ideas here to occupy compensation researchers for decades to come.
AB  - How can researchers bridge the gap between compensation theory and the compensation pressures today's complex organizations face? The book ?Compensation in Organizations: Current Research and Practice,? edited by Sara L. Rynes and Barry Gerhart, tackles this problem head-on. This book is squarely aimed at academic researchers, and Rynes and Gerhart know their audience. Each chapter begins with a brief ?state-of-the-field? overview, addressing a defined segment of compensation research and theory. The chapter authors then identify compensation issues and practices that current knowledge does not address. In essence, in each chapter a research agenda for the applied researcher is laid out. The book does a great job of identifying the ?holes? that have not been addressed by the compensation literature; there are enough research ideas here to occupy compensation researchers for decades to come.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.4011992
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2001.4011992
Y2  - 2026/04/24
